# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: unicode-bidi-web
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] A **bidirectional text** contains two text directionalities, right-to-left (RTL) and left-to-right (LTR).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] It generally involves text containing different types of alphabets, but may also refer to boustrophedon, which is changing text direction in each row.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] An example is the RTL Hebrew name Sarah: שרה, spelled sin (ש) on the right, resh (ר) in the middle, and heh (ה) on the left.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Many computer programs failed to display this correctly, because they were designed to display text in one direction only.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Some so-called right-to-left scripts such as the Persian script and Arabic are mostly, but not exclusively, right-to-left—mathematical expressions, numeric dates and numbers bearing units are embedded from left to right.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] That also happens if text from a left-to-right language such as English is embedded in them; or vice versa, if Arabic is embedded in a left-to-right script such as English.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Bidirectional script support is the capability of a computer system to correctly display bidirectional text.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] The term is often shortened to "**BiDi**" or "**bidi**".
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Early computer installations were designed only to support a single writing system, typically for left-to-right scripts based on the Latin alphabet only.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Adding new character sets and character encodings enabled a number of other left-to-right scripts to be supported, but did not easily support right-to-left scripts such as Arabic or Hebrew, and mixing the two was not practical.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Right-to-left scripts were introduced through encodings like ISO/IEC 8859-6 and ISO/IEC 8859-8, storing the letters (usually) in writing and reading order.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] It is possible to simply flip the left-to-right display order to a right-to-left display order, but doing this sacrifices the ability to correctly display left-to-right scripts.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] With bidirectional script support, it is possible to mix characters from different scripts on the same page, regardless of writing direction.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] In particular, the Unicode standard provides foundations for complete BiDi support, with detailed rules as to how mixtures of left-to-right and right-to-left scripts are to be encoded and displayed.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] The Unicode standard calls for characters to be ordered 'logically', i.e. in the sequence they are intended to be interpreted, as opposed to 'visually', the sequence they appear.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] This distinction is relevant for bidi support because at any bidi transition, the visual presentation ceases to be the 'logical' one.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Thus, in order to offer bidi support, Unicode prescribes an algorithm for how to convert the logical sequence of characters into the correct visual presentation.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] For this purpose, the Unicode encoding standard divides all its characters into one of four types: 'strong', 'weak', 'neutral', and 'explicit formatting'.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Strong characters are those with a definite direction.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Examples of this type of character include most alphabetic characters, syllabic characters, Han ideographs, non-European or non-Arabic digits, and punctuation characters that are specific to only those scripts.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Weak characters are those with vague direction.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Examples of this type of character include European digits, Eastern Arabic-Indic digits, arithmetic symbols, and currency symbols.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Neutral characters have direction indeterminable without context.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Examples include paragraph separators, tabs, and most other whitespace characters.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Punctuation symbols that are common to many scripts, such as the colon, comma, full-stop, and the no-break-space also fall within this category.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Explicit formatting characters, also referred to as "directional formatting characters", are special Unicode sequences that direct the algorithm to modify its default behavior.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] These characters are subdivided into "marks", "embeddings", "isolates", and "overrides".
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Their effects continue until the occurrence of either a paragraph separator, or a "pop" character.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] If a "weak" character is followed by another "weak" character, the algorithm will look at the first neighbouring "strong" character.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Sometimes this leads to unintentional display errors.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] These errors are corrected or prevented with "pseudo-strong" characters.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Such Unicode control characters are called *marks*.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] The mark (U+200E LEFT-TO-RIGHT MARK (LRM) or U+200F RIGHT-TO-LEFT MARK (RLM)) is to be inserted into a location to make an enclosed weak character inherit its writing direction.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] For example, to correctly display the U+2122 ™ TRADE MARK SIGN for an English name brand (LTR) in an Arabic (RTL) passage, an LRM mark is inserted after the trademark symbol if the symbol is not followed by LTR text (e.g.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] If the LRM mark is not added, the weak character ™ will be neighbored by a strong LTR character and a strong RTL character.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Hence, in an RTL context, it will be considered to be RTL, and displayed in an incorrect order (e.g.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] The "embedding" directional formatting characters are the classical Unicode method of explicit formatting, and as of Unicode 6.3, are being discouraged in favor of "isolates".
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] An "embedding" signals that a piece of text is to be treated as directionally distinct.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] The text within the scope of the embedding formatting characters is not independent of the surrounding text.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Also, characters within an embedding can affect the ordering of characters outside.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Unicode 6.3 recognized that directional embeddings usually have too strong an effect on their surroundings and are thus unnecessarily difficult to use.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] The "isolate" directional formatting characters signal that a piece of text is to be treated as directionally isolated from its surroundings.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] As of Unicode 6.3, these are the formatting characters that are being encouraged in new documents – once target platforms are known to support them.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] These formatting characters were introduced after it became apparent that directional embeddings usually have too strong an effect on their surroundings and are thus unnecessarily difficult to use.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Unlike the legacy 'embedding' directional formatting characters, 'isolate' characters have no effect on the ordering of the text outside their scope.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Isolates can be nested, and may be placed within embeddings and overrides.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] The "override" directional formatting characters allow for special cases, such as for part numbers (e.g. to force a part number made of mixed English, digits and Hebrew letters to be written from right to left), and are recommended to be avoided wherever possible.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] As is true of the other directional formatting characters, "overrides" can be nested one inside another, and in embeddings and isolates.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Using U+202D LEFT-TO-RIGHT OVERRIDE will switch the text direction from left-to-right to right-to-left.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Similarly, using U+202E RIGHT-TO-LEFT OVERRIDE will switch the text direction from right-to-left to left-to-right based on the Unicode Bidirectional Algorithm.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] The "pop" directional formatting character, encoded at U+202C POP DIRECTIONAL FORMATTING, terminates the scope of the most recent "embedding", "override", or "isolate".
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] In the algorithm, each sequence of concatenated strong characters is called a "run".
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] A "weak" character that is located between two "strong" characters with the same orientation will inherit their orientation.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] A "weak" character that is located between two "strong" characters with a different writing direction will inherit the main context's writing direction (in an LTR document the character will become LTR, in an RTL document, it will become RTL).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Unicode bidirectional characters are used in the Trojan Source vulnerability.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Visual Studio Code highlights BiDi control characters since version 1.62 released in October 2021.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Visual Studio highlights BiDi control characters since version 17.0.3 released on December 14, 2021.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Egyptian hieroglyphs were written bidirectionally, where the signs that had a distinct "head" or "tail" faced the beginning of the line.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Chinese characters can be written in either direction as well as vertically (top to bottom then right to left), especially in signs (such as plaques), but the orientation of the individual characters does not change.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] This can often be seen on tour buses in China, where the company name customarily runs from the front of the vehicle to its rear — that is, from right to left on the right side of the bus, and from left to right on the left side of the bus.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] English texts on the right side of the vehicle are also quite commonly written in reverse order.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Likewise, other CJK scripts made up of the same square characters, such as the Japanese writing system and Korean writing system, can also be written in any direction, although horizontally left-to-right, top-to-bottom and vertically top-to-bottom right-to-left are the two most common forms.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Boustrophedon is a writing style found in ancient Greek inscriptions, in Old Sabaic (an Old South Arabian language) and in Hungarian runes.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] This method of writing alternates direction, and usually reverses the individual characters, on each successive line.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Moon type is an embossed adaptation of the Latin alphabet invented as a tactile alphabet for the blind.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Initially the text changed direction (but not character orientation) at the end of the lines.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Special embossed lines connected the end of a line and the beginning of the next.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/bidirectional-text] Around 1990, it changed to a left-to-right orientation.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/css-direction] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/css-direction] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/css-direction] The **`direction`** CSS property sets the direction of text, table and grid columns, and horizontal overflow.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/css-direction] Use `rtl` for languages written from right to left (like Hebrew or Arabic), and `ltr` for those written from left to right (like English and most other languages).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/css-direction] Note that text direction is usually defined within a document (e.g., with HTML's `dir` attribute) rather than through direct use of the `direction` property.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/css-direction] Text and other elements go from left to right.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/css-direction] Text and other elements go from right to left.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/css-direction] For the `direction` property to have any effect on inline-level elements, the `unicode-bidi` property's value must be `embed` or `override`.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/css-direction] The property sets the base text direction of block-level elements and the direction of embeddings created by the `unicode-bidi` property.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/css-direction] It also sets the default alignment of text, block-level elements, and the direction that cells flow within a table or grid row.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/css-direction] Unlike the `dir` attribute in HTML, the `direction` property is not inherited from table columns into table cells, since CSS inheritance follows the document tree, and table cells are inside of rows but not inside of columns.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/css-direction] The `direction` and `unicode-bidi` properties are the only two properties which are not affected by the `all` shorthand property.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/css-direction] In the example below are two strings of text, both which are displaying using `direction: rtl`.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/css-direction] While the Arabic text is displayed correctly with this setting, the English text now has a full stop in an unusual location.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdi] It’s been available across browsers since January 2020.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdi] The **`<bdi>`** HTML element tells the browser's bidirectional algorithm to treat the text it contains in isolation from its surrounding text.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdi] It's particularly useful when a website dynamically inserts some text and doesn't know the directionality of the text being inserted.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdi] Bidirectional text is text that may contain both sequences of characters that are arranged left-to-right (LTR) and sequences of characters that are arranged right-to-left (RTL), such as an Arabic quotation embedded in an English string.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdi] Browsers implement the Unicode Bidirectional Algorithm to handle this.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdi] In this algorithm, characters are given an implicit directionality: for example, Latin characters are treated as LTR while Arabic characters are treated as RTL.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdi] Some other characters (such as spaces and some punctuation) are treated as neutral and are assigned directionality based on that of their surrounding characters.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdi] Usually, the bidirectional algorithm will do the right thing without the author having to provide any special markup but, occasionally, the algorithm needs help.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdi] The `<bdi>` element is used to wrap a span of text and instructs the bidirectional algorithm to treat this text in isolation from its surroundings.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdi] If `EMBEDDED-TEXT` is LTR, this works fine.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdi] But if `EMBEDDED-TEXT` is RTL, then `- 1` will be treated as RTL text (because it consists of neutral and weak characters).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdi] If you know the directionality of `EMBEDDED-TEXT` in advance, you can fix this problem by wrapping `EMBEDDED-TEXT` in a `<span>` with the `dir` attribute set to the known directionality.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdi] But if you don't know the directionality - for example, because `EMBEDDED-TEXT` is being read from a database or entered by the user - you should use `<bdi>` to prevent the directionality of `EMBEDDED-TEXT` from affecting its surroundings.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdi] Though the same visual effect can be achieved using the CSS rule `unicode-bidi: isolate` on a `<span>` or another text-formatting element, HTML authors should not use this approach because it is not semantic and browsers are allowed to ignore CSS styling.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdi] Embedding the characters in `<span dir="auto">` has the same effect as using `<bdi>`, but its semantics are less clear.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdi] Like all other HTML elements, this element supports the global attributes, except that the `dir` attribute behaves differently than normal: it defaults to `auto`, meaning its value is never inherited from the parent element.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdi] This means that unless you specify a value of either `rtl` or `ltr` for `dir`, the user agent will determine the correct directionality to use based on the contents of the `<bdi>`.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdi] This example lists the winners of a competition using `<span>` elements only.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdi] This example lists the winners of a competition using `<span>` elements only, and one of the winners has a name consisting of RTL text.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdi] This example lists the winners of a competition using `<bdi>` elements.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdo] The **`<bdo>`** HTML element overrides the current directionality of text, so that the text within is rendered in a different direction.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdo] The text's characters are drawn from the starting point in the given direction; the individual characters' orientation is not affected (so characters don't get drawn backward, for example).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdo] This element's attributes include the global attributes.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/element-bdo] The direction in which text should be rendered in this element's contents.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] A **writing system** is any conventional system for representing a particular language using a set of symbols (called a ***script***), as well as the rules those symbols encode.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] The earliest of conventional writing systems appeared during the late 4th millennium BC.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Throughout history, each independently invented writing system gradually emerged from a system of proto-writing, where a small number of ideographs were used in a manner incapable of fully encoding language, and thus lacking the ability to express a broad range of ideas.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Writing systems are generally classified according to how their symbols, called *graphemes*, relate to units of language.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Phonetic writing systems – which include alphabets and syllabaries – use graphemes that correspond to sounds in the corresponding spoken language.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Alphabets use graphemes called *letters* that generally correspond to spoken phonemes.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] They are typically divided into three sub-types: *Pure alphabets* use letters to represent both consonant and vowel sounds, *abjads* generally only use letters representing consonant sounds, and *abugidas* use letters representing consonant–vowel pairs.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Syllabaries use graphemes called *syllabograms* that represent entire syllables or moras.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] By contrast, logographic (or *morphographic*) writing systems use graphemes that represent the units of meaning in a language, such as its words or morphemes.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Alphabets typically use fewer than 100 distinct symbols, while syllabaries and logographies may use hundreds or thousands, respectively.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] According to most contemporary definitions, writing is a visual and tactile notation representing language.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] As such, the use of writing by a community presupposes an analysis of the structure of language at some level.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] The symbols used in writing correspond systematically to functional units of either a spoken or signed language.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] This definition excludes a broader class of symbolic markings, such as drawings and maps.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] A text is any instance of written material, including transcriptions of spoken material.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] The act of composing and recording a text is referred to as *writing*, and the act of viewing and interpreting the text as *reading*.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] The relationship between writing and language more broadly has been the subject of philosophical analysis as early as Aristotle (384–322 BC).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] While the use of language is universal across human societies, writing is not; writing emerged much more recently, and was independently invented in only a handful of locations throughout history.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] While most spoken languages have not been written, all written languages have been predicated on an existing spoken language.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] When those with signed languages as their first language read writing associated with a spoken language, this functions as literacy in a second, acquired language.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Hindustani) can be written using multiple writing systems, and a writing system can also represent multiple languages.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] For example, Chinese characters have been used to write multiple languages throughout the Sinosphere – including the Vietnamese language from at least the 13th century, until their replacement with the Latin-based Vietnamese alphabet in the 20th century.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] While researchers of writing systems generally use some of the same core terminology, precise definitions and interpretations can vary by author, often depending on their theoretical approach.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] A grapheme is the basic functional unit of a writing system.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Graphemes are generally defined as minimally significant elements that, when taken together, comprise the set of symbols from which texts may be constructed.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] All writing systems require a set of defined graphemes, collectively called a *script*.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] The concept of the grapheme is similar to that of the phoneme in the study of spoken languages.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Likewise, as many sonically distinct phones may function as the same phoneme depending on the speaker, dialect, and context, many visually distinct glyphs (or *graphs*) may be identified as the same grapheme.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] These variant glyphs are known as the *allographs* of a grapheme: For example, the lowercase letter ⟨a⟩ may be represented by the double-storey |a| and single-storey |ɑ| shapes, or others written in cursive, block, or printed styles.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] 'correct writing') refers to the rules and conventions for writing shared by a community, including the ordering of and relationship between graphemes.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Particularly for alphabets, orthography includes the concept of spelling.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] For example, English orthography includes uppercase and lowercase forms for 26 letters of the Latin alphabet (with these graphemes corresponding to various phonemes), punctuation marks (mostly non-phonemic), and other symbols, such as numerals.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Writing systems may be regarded as complete if they are able to represent all that may be expressed in the spoken language, while a partial writing system cannot represent the spoken language in its entirety.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] In each instance, writing emerged from systems of proto-writing, though historically most proto-writing systems did not produce writing systems.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Proto-writing uses ideographic and mnemonic symbols to communicate, but lacks the capability to fully encode language.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Cuneiform was closely followed by Egyptian hieroglyphs.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] It is generally agreed that the two systems were invented independently from one another; both evolved from proto-writing systems between 3400 and 3100 BC, with the earliest coherent texts dated c.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Chinese characters emerged independently in the Yellow River valley c.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] There is no evidence of contact between China and the literate peoples of the Near East, and the Mesopotamian and Chinese approaches for representing sound and meaning are distinct.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] The Mesoamerican writing systems, including Olmec and the Maya script, are likewise associated with an independent invention.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] With each independent invention of writing, the ideographs used in proto-writing were decoupled from the direct representation of ideas, and gradually came to represent words instead.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] This occurred via application of the rebus principle, where a symbol was appropriated to represent an additional word that happened to be similar in pronunciation to the word for the idea originally represented by the symbol.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] This allowed words without concrete visualizations to be represented by symbols for the first time; the gradual shift from ideographic symbols to those wholly representing language took place over centuries, and required the conscious analysis of a given language by those attempting to write it.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] 2000 BC), found on different types of artefacts produced by the Indus Valley Civilization on the Indian subcontinent, remains undeciphered, and whether it functioned as true writing is not agreed upon.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Alphabetic writing descends from previous morphographic writing, and first appeared c.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] 1800 BC to write a Semitic language spoken in the Sinai Peninsula.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Most of the world's alphabets either descend directly from this Proto-Sinaitic script, or were directly inspired by its design.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Descendants include the Phoenician alphabet (c.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] 1050 BC), and its child in the Greek alphabet (c.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] The Latin alphabet, which descended from the Greek alphabet, is by far the most common script used by writing systems.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Writing systems are most often classified according to what units of language a system's graphemes correspond to.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] At the most basic level, writing systems can be either phonographic (lit.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] 'sound writing') when graphemes represent units of sound in a language, or morphographic ('form writing') when graphemes represent units of meaning (such as words or morphemes).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Depending on the author, the older term *logographic* ('word writing') is often used, either with the same meaning as *morphographic*, or specifically in reference to systems where the basic unit being written is the word.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Recent scholarship generally prefers *morphographic* over *logographic*, with the latter seen as potentially vague or misleading – in part because systems usually operate on the level of morphemes, not words.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Some authors make a distinct primary division – between *pleremic* (from Greek *plḗrēs* 'full') systems with graphemes that have semantic value in isolation (like logographs), and *cenemic* (from Greek *kenós* 'empty') systems with graphemes that lack any such separable meaning (like letters).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Many classifications define three primary categories, where phonographic systems are subdivided into syllabic and alphabetic (or *segmental*) systems.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Syllabaries use symbols called syllabograms to represent syllables or moras.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Alphabets use symbols called letters that correspond to spoken phonemes (or more technically, to diaphonemes).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Alphabets are generally classified into three subtypes, with abjads having letters for consonants, pure alphabets having letters for both consonants and vowels, and abugidas having characters that correspond to consonant–vowel pairs.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] David Diringer proposed a five-fold classification of writing systems, comprising pictographic scripts, ideographic scripts, analytic transitional scripts, phonetic scripts, and alphabetic scripts.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] In practice, writing systems are classified according to the primary type of symbols used, and typically include exceptional cases where symbols function differently.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] For example, logographs found within phonetic systems like English include the ampersand ⟨&⟩ and the numerals ⟨0⟩, ⟨1⟩, etc. – which correspond to specific words (*and*, *zero*, *one*, etc.) and not to the underlying sounds.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Most writing systems can be described as mixed systems that feature elements of both phonography and morphography.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] A logogram is a character that represents a morpheme within a language.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Chinese characters represent the only major logographic writing systems still in use: they have historically been used to write the varieties of Chinese, as well as Japanese, Korean, Vietnamese, and other languages of the Sinosphere.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] As each character represents a single unit of meaning, thousands are required to write all the words of a language.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] If the logograms do not adequately represent all meanings and words of a language, written language can be confusing or ambiguous to the reader.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Logograms are sometimes conflated with ideograms, symbols which graphically represent abstract ideas; most linguists now reject this characterization.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Chinese characters are often semantic–phonetic compounds, which include a component related to the character's meaning, and a component that gives a hint for its pronunciation.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] A syllabary is a set of written symbols (called *syllabograms*) that represent either syllables or moras – a unit of prosody that is often but not always a syllable in length.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Syllabaries are best suited to languages with relatively simple syllable structure, since a different symbol is needed for every syllable.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] For example, the Japanese writing system has two kana syllabaries (hiragana and katakana) intended for use in distinct circumstances; both have syllabograms for each of the roughly 100 moras found in Japanese.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] By contrast, English features complex syllable structures, with a relatively large inventory of vowels and complex consonant clusters – for a total of 15–16 thousand distinct syllables.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Some syllabaries have larger inventories: the Yi script contains 756 different symbols.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] An alphabet uses symbols (called *letters*) that correspond to the phonemes of a language, e.g. its vowels and consonants.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] However, these correspondences are rarely uncomplicated, and spelling is often mediated by other factors than just which sounds are used by a speaker.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] The word *alphabet* is derived from *alpha* and *beta*, the names for the first two letters in the Greek alphabet.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] An abjad is an alphabet whose letters only represent the consonantal sounds of a language.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] They were the first alphabets to develop historically, with most used to write Semitic languages, and originally deriving from the Proto-Sinaitic script.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] The morphology of Semitic languages is particularly suited to this approach, as the denotation of vowels is generally redundant.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Optional markings for vowels may be used for some abjads, but are generally limited to applications like education.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Many pure alphabets were derived from abjads through the addition of dedicated vowel letters, as with the derivation of the Greek alphabet from the Phoenician alphabet c.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] *Abjad* is the word for "alphabet" in Arabic, and analogously derives from the traditional order of letters in the Arabic alphabet (*'alif*, *bā'*, *jīm*, *dāl*).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] An abugida is a type of alphabet with symbols corresponding to consonant–vowel pairs, where basic symbols for each consonant are associated with an inherent vowel by default, and other possible vowels for each consonant are indicated via predictable modifications made to the basic symbols.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] In an abugida, there may be a sign for *k* with no vowel, but also one for *ka* (if *a* is the inherent vowel), and *ke* is written by modifying the *ka* sign in a way consistent with how *la* would be modified to get *le*.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] In many abugidas, modification consists of the addition of a vowel sign; other possibilities include rotation of the basic sign, or addition of diacritics.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] While true syllabaries have one symbol per syllable and no systematic visual similarity, the graphic similarity in most abugidas stems from their origins as abjads – with added symbols comprising markings for different vowels added onto a pre-existing base symbol.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] The largest single group of abugidas is the Brahmic family of scripts, however, which includes nearly all the scripts used in India and Southeast Asia.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] The name *abugida* was derived by linguist Peter T.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] 1951) from the first four characters of an order of the Geʽez script, which is used for certain Nilo-Saharan and Afro-Asiatic languages of Ethiopia and Eritrea.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Originally proposed as a category by Geoffrey Sampson, a featural system uses symbols representing sub-phonetic elements – e.g. those traits that can be used to distinguish between and analyse a language's phonemes, such as their voicing or place of articulation.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] The only prominent example of a featural system is the Hangul script used to write Korean, where featural symbols are combined into letters, which are in turn joined into syllabic blocks.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Many scholars, including John DeFrancis, reject a characterization of Hangul as a featural system – with arguments including that Korean writers do not themselves think in these terms when writing – or question the viability of Sampson's category altogether.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] As Hangul was consciously created by literate experts, Daniels characterizes it as a "sophisticated grammatogeny" – a writing system intentionally designed for a specific purpose, as opposed to having evolved gradually over time.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Other featural grammatogenies include shorthands developed by professionals and constructed scripts created by hobbyists and creatives, like the Tengwar script designed by J.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Tolkien to write the Elven languages he also constructed.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Many of these feature advanced graphic designs corresponding to phonological properties.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] The basic unit of writing in these systems can map to anything from phonemes to words.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] It has been shown that even the Latin script has sub-character features in its lowercase letters.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] All writing is linear in the broadest sense – i.e., the spatial arrangement of symbols indicates the order in which they should be read.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] On a more granular level, systems with discontinuous marks like diacritics can be characterized as less linear than those without.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] In the initial historical distinction, *linear* writing systems (e.g. the Phoenician alphabet) generally form glyphs as a series of connected lines or strokes, while systems that generally use discrete, more pictorial marks (e.g. cuneiform) are sometimes termed *non-linear*.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] The historical abstraction of logographs into phonographs is often associated with a linearization of the script.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] In Braille, raised bumps on the writing substrate are used to encode non-linear symbols.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] The original system – which Louis Braille (1809–1852) invented in order to allow people with visual impairments to read and write – used characters that corresponded to the letters of the Latin alphabet.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Moreover, that Braille is equivalent to visual writing systems in function demonstrates that the phenomenon of writing is fundamentally spatial in nature, not merely visual.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] In left-to-right scripts (LTR), horizontal rows are sequenced from top to bottom on a page, with each row read from left to right.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Right-to-left scripts (RTL), which use the opposite directionality, include the Arabic alphabet.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Egyptian hieroglyphs were written either left-to-right or right-to-left, with the animal and human glyphs turned to face the beginning of the line.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] The early alphabet did not have a fixed direction, and was written both vertically and horizontally; it was most commonly written boustrophedonically: starting in one horizontal direction, then turning at the end of the line and reversing direction.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] The right-to-left direction of the Phoenician alphabet initially stabilized after c.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Left-to-right writing has an advantage that, since most people are right-handed, the hand does not interfere with what is being written (which, when inked, may not have dried yet) as the hand is to the right side of the pen.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] The Greek alphabet and its successors settled on a left-to-right pattern, from the top to the bottom of the page.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Other scripts, such as Arabic and Hebrew, came to be written right to left.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Scripts that historically incorporate Chinese characters have traditionally been written vertically in columns arranged from right to left, while a horizontal direction from left to right was only widely adopted in the 20th century due to Western influence.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Several scripts used in the Philippines and Indonesia, such as Hanunoo, are traditionally written with lines moving away from the writer, from bottom to top, but are read left to right; ogham is written from bottom to top, commonly on the corner of a stone.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] The ancient Libyco-Berber alphabet was also written from bottom to top.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Writing systems, especially alphabets, often include characters that can represent multiple sound values, or conversely sound values that can be represented by multiple characters – this phenomenon is referred to as *polyvalence*.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Orthographies with lower or higher polyvalence are referred to as *shallow* or *deep* respectively.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] While polyvalent graphemes are often perceived as defects, they can serve to distinguish homophonic words, and to indicate etymological or semantic connections between words not clear from pronunciation alone – e.g. between English *sign* and *signal* or *child* and *children*.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Specifically, an orthographic relationship where one grapheme may represent multiple sound values can be termed *polyphony*, while a relationship where one sound value may be represented by multiple graphemes can be termed *polygraphy*.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] Scholars have increasingly analysed different patterns of phonological spellings versus morphological spellings in a writing system as being better suited depending on the characteristics of the spoken language, with neither principle being ideal in all circumstances.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/right-to-left-script] While not adhering strictly to phonological rules, morphological spellings often follow other patterns that allow for transparent identification and parsing by readers and writers.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-bidi] The **`unicode-bidi`** CSS property, together with the `direction` property, determines how bidirectional text in a document is handled.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-bidi] For example, if a block of content contains both left-to-right and right-to-left text, the user-agent uses a complex Unicode algorithm to decide how to display the text.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-bidi] The `unicode-bidi` property overrides this algorithm and allows the developer to control the text embedding.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-bidi] The `unicode-bidi` and `direction` properties are the only properties that are not affected by the `all` shorthand.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-bidi] The element does not offer an additional level of embedding with respect to the bidirectional algorithm.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-bidi] For inline elements, implicit reordering works across element boundaries.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-bidi] If the element is inline, this value opens an additional level of embedding with respect to the bidirectional algorithm.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-bidi] The direction of this embedding level is given by the `direction` property.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-bidi] For inline elements this creates an override.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-bidi] For block container elements this creates an override for inline-level descendants not within another block container element.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-bidi] This means that inside the element, reordering is strictly in sequence according to the `direction` property; the implicit part of the bidirectional algorithm is ignored.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-bidi] This keyword indicates that the element's container directionality should be calculated without considering the content of this element.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-bidi] The element is therefore *isolated* from its siblings.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-bidi] When applying its bidirectional-resolution algorithm, its container element treats it as one or several `U+FFFC Object Replacement Character`, i.e., like an image.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-bidi] This keyword applies the isolation behavior of the `isolate` keyword to the surrounding content and the override behavior of the `bidi-override` keyword to the inner content.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-bidi] This keyword makes the elements directionality calculated without considering its parent bidirectional state or the value of the `direction` property.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-bidi] The directionality is calculated using the P2 and P3 rules of the Unicode Bidirectional Algorithm.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-bidi] This value allows the display of data that is already formatted using a tool following the Unicode Bidirectional Algorithm.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Unicode has largely supplanted the previous environment of myriad incompatible character sets used within different locales and on different computer architectures.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The entire repertoire of these sets, plus many additional characters, were merged into the single Unicode set.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Unicode is used to encode the vast majority of text on the Internet, including most web pages, and relevant Unicode support has become a common consideration in contemporary software development.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Unicode is ultimately capable of encoding more than 1.1 million characters.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The Unicode character repertoire is synchronized with ISO/IEC 10646, each being code-for-code identical with one another.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] However, *The Unicode Standard* is more than just a repertoire within which characters are assigned.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] To aid developers and designers, the standard also provides charts and reference data, as well as annexes explaining concepts germane to various scripts, providing guidance for their implementation.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Topics covered by these annexes include character normalization, character composition and decomposition, collation, and directionality.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Unicode encodes 3,790 emoji, with the continued development thereof conducted by the Consortium as a part of the standard.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The widespread adoption of Unicode was in large part responsible for the initial popularization of emoji outside of Japan.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Unicode text is processed and stored as binary data using one of several encodings, which define how to translate the standard's abstracted codes for characters into sequences of bytes.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] *The Unicode Standard* itself defines three encodings: UTF-8, UTF-16, and UTF-32, though several others exist.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] UTF-8 is the most widely used by a large margin, in part due to its backwards-compatibility with ASCII.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Unicode was originally designed with the intent of transcending limitations present in all text encodings designed up to that point: each encoding was relied upon for use in its own context, but with no particular expectation of compatibility with any other.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Indeed, any two encodings chosen were often totally unworkable when used together, with text encoded in one interpreted as garbage characters by the other.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Most encodings had only been designed to facilitate interoperation between a handful of scripts—often primarily between a given script and Latin characters—not between a large number of scripts, and not with all of the scripts supported being treated in a consistent manner.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The philosophy that underpins Unicode seeks to encode the underlying characters—graphemes and grapheme-like units—rather than graphical distinctions considered mere variant glyphs thereof, that are instead best handled by the typeface, through the use of markup, or by some other means.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] In particularly complex cases, such as the treatment of orthographical variants in Han characters, there is considerable disagreement regarding which differences justify their own encodings, and which are only graphical variants of other characters.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] At the most abstract level, Unicode assigns a unique number called a *code point* to each character.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Many issues of visual representation—including size, shape, and style—are intended to be up to the discretion of the software actually rendering the text, such as a web browser or word processor.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] However, partially with the intent of encouraging rapid adoption, the simplicity of this original model has become somewhat more elaborate over time, and various pragmatic concessions have been made over the course of the standard's development.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The first 256 code points mirror the ISO/IEC 8859-1 standard, with the intent of trivializing the conversion of text already written in Western European scripts.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] To preserve the distinctions made by different legacy encodings, therefore allowing for conversion between them and Unicode without any loss of information, many characters nearly identical to others, in both appearance and intended function, were given distinct code points.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] For example, the Halfwidth and Fullwidth Forms block encompasses a full semantic duplicate of the Latin alphabet, because legacy CJK encodings contained both "fullwidth" (matching the width of CJK characters) and "halfwidth" (matching ordinary Latin script) characters.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The origins of Unicode can be traced back to the 1980s, to a group of individuals with connections to Xerox's Character Code Standard (XCCS).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] In 1987, Xerox employee Joe Becker, along with Apple employees Lee Collins and Mark Davis, started investigating the practicalities of creating a universal character set.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] With additional input from Peter Fenwick and Dave Opstad, Becker published a draft proposal for an "international/multilingual text character encoding system in August 1988, tentatively called Unicode".
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] He explained that "the name 'Unicode' is intended to suggest a unique, unified, universal encoding".
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] In early 1989, the Unicode working group expanded to include Ken Whistler and Mike Kernaghan of Metaphor, Karen Smith-Yoshimura and Joan Aliprand of Research Libraries Group, and Glenn Wright of Sun Microsystems.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The Research Libraries Group had an existing solution for East Asian character sets, which became one of the inputs to the Unicode character set.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] In 1990, Michel Suignard and Asmus Freytag of Microsoft and NeXT's Rick McGowan had also joined the group.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] By the end of 1990, most of the work of remapping existing standards had been completed, and a final review draft of Unicode was ready.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The Unicode Consortium was incorporated in California on 3 January 1991, and the first volume of *The Unicode Standard* was published that October.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The second volume, now adding Han ideographs, was published in June 1992.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] In 1996, a surrogate character mechanism was implemented in Unicode 2.0, so that Unicode was no longer restricted to 16 bits.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] This increased the Unicode codespace to over a million code points, which allowed for the encoding of many historic scripts, such as Egyptian hieroglyphs, and thousands of rarely used or obsolete characters that had not been anticipated for inclusion in the standard.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Among these characters are various rarely used CJK characters—many mainly being used in proper names, making them far more necessary for a universal encoding than the original Unicode architecture envisioned.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The Unicode Consortium is a non-profit organization that coordinates Unicode's development.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Full members include most of the main computer software and hardware companies (and few others) with any interest in text-processing standards, including Adobe, Apple, Google, IBM, Meta (previously as Facebook), Microsoft, Netflix, and SAP.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Over the years several countries or government agencies have been members of the Unicode Consortium.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The Consortium has the ambitious goal of eventually replacing existing character encoding schemes with Unicode and its standard Unicode Transformation Format (UTF) schemes, as many of the existing schemes are limited in size and scope and are incompatible with multilingual environments.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The **Unicode Bulldog Award** is given to people deemed to be influential in Unicode's development, with recipients including Tatsuo Kobayashi, Thomas Milo, Roozbeh Pournader, Ken Lunde, and Michael Everson.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] As of September 2025, a total of 172 scripts (alphabets, abugidas and syllabaries) are included in Unicode, covering most major writing systems in use today.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] There are still scripts that are not yet encoded, particularly those mainly used in historical, liturgical, and academic contexts.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Further additions of characters to the already encoded scripts, as well as symbols, in particular for mathematics and music also occur.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The Unicode Roadmap Committee (Michael Everson, Rick McGowan, Ken Whistler, V.S.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Umamaheswaran) maintain the list of scripts that are candidates or potential candidates for encoding and their tentative code block assignments on the Unicode Roadmap page of the Unicode Consortium website.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] For some scripts on the Roadmap, such as Jurchen and Khitan large script, encoding proposals have been made and they are working their way through the approval process.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] For other scripts, such as Numidian and Rongorongo, no proposal has yet been made, and they await agreement on character repertoire and other details from the user communities involved.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] There is also a Medieval Unicode Font Initiative focused on special Latin medieval characters.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Part of these proposals has been already included in Unicode.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The Script Encoding Initiative (SEI), a project created by Deborah Anderson at the University of California, Berkeley, was founded in 2002 with the goal of funding proposals for scripts not yet encoded in the standard.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Now run by Anushah Hossain, SEI has become a major source of proposed additions to the standard in recent years.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Although SEI collaborates with the Unicode Consortium and the ISO/IEC 10646 standards process, it operates independently, supporting the technical, linguistic, and historical research needed to prepare formal proposals.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] SEI maintains a database of scripts that have yet to be encoded in the Unicode Standard on the project's website.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The Unicode Consortium together with the ISO have developed a shared repertoire following the initial publication of *The Unicode Standard*: Unicode and the ISO's Universal Coded Character Set (UCS) use identical character names and code points.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] However, the Unicode versions do differ from their ISO equivalents in two significant ways.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] While the UCS is a simple character map, Unicode specifies the rules, algorithms, and properties necessary to achieve interoperability between different platforms and languages.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Thus, *The Unicode Standard* includes more information, covering in-depth topics such as bitwise encoding, collation, and rendering.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] It also provides a comprehensive catalog of character properties, including those needed for supporting bidirectional text, as well as visual charts and reference data sets to aid implementers.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Previously, *The Unicode Standard* was sold as a print volume containing the complete core specification, standard annexes, and code charts.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] However, version 5.0, published in 2006, was the last version printed this way.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Starting with version 5.2, only the core specification, published as a print-on-demand paperback, may be purchased.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The full text, on the other hand, is published as a free PDF on the Unicode website.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] A practical reason for this publication method highlights the second significant difference between the UCS and Unicode—the frequency with which updated versions are released and new characters added.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] *The Unicode Standard* has regularly released annual expanded versions, occasionally with more than one version released in a calendar year and with rare cases where the scheduled release had to be postponed.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] For instance, in April 2020, a month after version 13.0 was published, the Unicode Consortium announced they had changed the intended release date for version 14.0, pushing it back six months to September 2021 due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Thus far, the following versions of *The Unicode Standard* have been published.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Update versions, which do not include any changes to character repertoire, are signified by the third number (e.g., "version 4.0.1") and are omitted in the table below.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The total number of graphic and format characters, excluding private use characters, control characters, noncharacters, and surrogate code points).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] 2.0 added Amendments 5, 6, and 72.1 added two characters from Amendment 18.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Plus Amendment 1, as well as the Lari sign, nine CJK unified ideographs, and 41 emoji; 9.0 added Amendment 2, as well as Adlam, Newa, Japanese TV symbols, and 74 emoji and symbols.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Plus 56 emoji, 285 hentaigana characters, and 3 Zanabazar Square characters11.0 added 46 Mtavruli Georgian capital letters, 5 CJK unified ideographs, and 66 emoji12.0 added 62 additional characters.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] In this normative notation, the two-character prefix `U+` always precedes a written code point, and the code points themselves are written as hexadecimal numbers.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] At least four hexadecimal digits are always written, with leading zeros prepended as needed.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] For example, the code point U+00F7 ÷ DIVISION SIGN is padded with two leading zeros, but U+13254 𓉔 EGYPTIAN HIEROGLYPH O004 () is not padded.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] There are a total of 1112064 valid code points within the codespace.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The Unicode codespace is divided into 17 *planes*, numbered 0 to 16.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Plane 0 is the Basic Multilingual Plane (BMP), and contains the most commonly used characters.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] All code points in the BMP are accessed as a single code unit in UTF-16 encoding and can be encoded in one, two or three bytes in UTF-8.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Code points in planes 1 through 16 (the *supplementary planes*) are accessed as surrogate pairs in UTF-16 and encoded in four bytes in UTF-8.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Within each plane, characters are allocated within named *blocks* of related characters.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The size of a block is always a multiple of 16, and is often a multiple of 128, but is otherwise arbitrary.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Characters required for a given script may be spread out over several different, potentially disjunct blocks within the codespace.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Each code point is assigned a classification, listed as the code point's General Category property.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Here, at the uppermost level code points are categorized as one of Letter, Mark, Number, Punctuation, Symbol, Separator, or Other.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Under each category, each code point is then further subcategorized.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] In most cases, other properties must be used to adequately describe all the characteristics of any given code point.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The 1024 points in the range U+D800–U+DBFF are known as *high-surrogate* code points, and code points in the range U+DC00–U+DFFF (1024 code points) are known as *low-surrogate* code points.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] A high-surrogate code point followed by a low-surrogate code point forms a *surrogate pair* in UTF-16 in order to represent code points greater than U+FFFF.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] In principle, these code points cannot otherwise be used, though in practice this rule is often ignored, especially when not using UTF-16.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] A small set of code points are guaranteed never to be assigned to characters, although third-parties may make independent use of them at their discretion.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] There are 66 of these *noncharacters*: U+FDD0–U+FDEF and the last two code points in each of the 17 planes (e.g.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The set of noncharacters is stable, and no new noncharacters will ever be defined.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Like surrogates, the rule that these cannot be used is often ignored, although the operation of the byte order mark assumes that U+FFFE will never be the first code point in a text.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The exclusion of surrogates and noncharacters leaves 1111998 code points available for use.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] 65 code points, the ranges U+0000–U+001F and U+007F–U+009F, are reserved as *control codes*, corresponding to the C0 and C1 control codes as defined in ISO/IEC 6429.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] U+0009 TAB, U+000A LINE FEED, and U+000D CARRIAGE RETURN are widely used in texts using Unicode.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] In a phenomenon known as mojibake, the C1 code points are improperly decoded according to the Windows-1252 codepage, previously widely used in Western European contexts.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Together, graphic, format, control code, and private use characters are collectively referred to as *assigned characters*.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] *Reserved* code points are those code points that are valid and available for use, but have not yet been assigned.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] As of Unicode 17.0, there are 814664 reserved code points.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The set of graphic and format characters defined by Unicode does not correspond directly to the repertoire of *abstract characters* representable under Unicode.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Unicode encodes characters by associating an abstract character with a particular code point.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] However, not all abstract characters are encoded as a single Unicode character, and some abstract characters may be represented in Unicode by a sequence of two or more characters.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] For example, a Latin small letter "i" with an ogonek, a dot above, and an acute accent, which is required in Lithuanian, is represented by the character sequence U+012F; U+0307; U+0301.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Unicode maintains a list of uniquely named character sequences for abstract characters that are not directly encoded in Unicode.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] All assigned characters have a unique and immutable name by which they are identified.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] This immutability has been guaranteed since version 2.0 of *The Unicode Standard* by its Name Stability policy.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] In cases where a name is seriously defective and misleading, or has a serious typographical error, a formal **alias** may be defined that applications are encouraged to use in place of the official character name.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] For example, U+A015 ꀕ YI SYLLABLE WU has the formal alias YI SYLLABLE ITERATION MARK, and U+FE18 ︘ PRESENTATION FORM FOR VERTICAL RIGHT WHITE LENTICULAR BRAKCET (sic) has the formal alias PRESENTATION FORM FOR VERTICAL RIGHT WHITE LENTICULAR BRA**CK**ET.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Unicode includes a mechanism for modifying characters that greatly extends the supported repertoire of glyphs.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] This covers the use of combining diacritical marks that may be added after the base character by the user.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Multiple combining diacritics may be simultaneously applied to the same character.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Unicode also contains precomposed versions of most letter/diacritic combinations in normal use.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] These make the conversion to and from legacy encodings simpler, and allow applications to use Unicode as an internal text format without having to implement combining characters.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] For example, `é` can be represented in Unicode as U+0065 e LATIN SMALL LETTER E followed by U+0301 ◌́ COMBINING ACUTE ACCENT, and equivalently as the precomposed character U+00E9 é LATIN SMALL LETTER E WITH ACUTE.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Thus, users often have multiple equivalent ways of encoding the same character.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The mechanism of canonical equivalence within *The Unicode Standard* ensures the practical interchangeability of these equivalent encodings.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] An example of this arises with the Korean alphabet Hangul: Unicode provides a mechanism for composing Hangul syllables from their individual Hangul Jamo subcomponents.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] However, it also provides 11172 combinations of precomposed syllables made from the most common jamo.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] CJK characters presently only have codes for uncomposable radicals and precomposed forms.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Most Han characters have either been intentionally composed from, or reconstructed as compositions of, simpler orthographic elements called radicals, so in principle Unicode could have enabled their composition as it did with Hangul.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] While this could have greatly reduced the number of required code points, as well as allowing the algorithmic synthesis of many arbitrary new characters, the complexities of character etymologies and the post-hoc nature of radical systems add immense complexity to the proposal.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Indeed, attempts to design CJK encodings on the basis of composing radicals have been met with difficulties resulting from the reality that Chinese characters do not decompose as simply or as regularly as Hangul does.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The CJK Radicals Supplement block is assigned to the range U+2E80–U+2EFF, and the Kangxi radicals are assigned to U+2F00–U+2FDF.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Many scripts, including Arabic and Devanāgarī, have special orthographic rules that require certain combinations of letterforms to be combined into special ligature forms.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Instructions are also embedded in fonts to tell the operating system how to properly output different character sequences.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] A simple solution to the placement of combining marks or diacritics is assigning the marks a width of zero and placing the glyph itself to the left or right of the left sidebearing (depending on the direction of the script they are intended to be used with).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] A mark handled this way will appear over whatever character precedes it, but will not adjust its position relative to the width or height of the base glyph; it may be visually awkward and it may overlap some glyphs.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Real stacking is impossible but can be approximated in limited cases (for example, Thai top-combining vowels and tone marks can just be at different heights to start with).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Generally, this approach is only effective in monospaced fonts but may be used as a fallback rendering method when more complex methods fail.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Several subsets of Unicode are standardized: Microsoft Windows since Windows NT 4.0 supports WGL-4 with 657 characters, which is considered to support all contemporary European languages using the Latin, Greek, or Cyrillic script.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Other standardized subsets of Unicode include the Multilingual European Subsets: MES-1 (Latin scripts only; 335 characters), MES-2 (Latin, Greek, and Cyrillic; 1062 characters) and MES-3A & MES-3B (two larger subsets, not shown here).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] MES-2 includes every character in MES-1 and WGL-4.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The standard DIN 91379 specifies a subset of Unicode letters, special characters, and sequences of letters and diacritic signs to allow the correct representation of names and to simplify data exchange in Europe.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] This standard supports all of the official languages of all European Union countries, as well as the German minority languages and the official languages of Iceland, Liechtenstein, Norway, and Switzerland.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] To allow the transliteration of names in other writing systems to the Latin script according to the relevant ISO standards, all necessary combinations of base letters and diacritic signs are provided.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Rendering software that cannot process a Unicode character appropriately often displays it as an open rectangle, or as U+FFFD to indicate the position of the unrecognized character.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Some systems have made attempts to provide more information about such characters.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Apple's Last Resort font will display a substitute glyph indicating the Unicode range of the character, and the SIL International's Unicode fallback font will display a box showing the hexadecimal scalar value of the character.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Several mechanisms have been specified for storing a series of code points as a series of bytes.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Unicode defines two mapping methods: the **Unicode Transformation Format** (UTF) encodings, and the **Universal Coded Character Set** (UCS) encodings.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] An encoding maps (possibly a subset of) the range of Unicode *code points* to sequences of values in some fixed-size range, termed *code units*.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] All UTF encodings map code points to a unique sequence of bytes.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The numbers in the names of the encodings indicate the number of bits per code unit (for UTF encodings) or the number of bytes per code unit (for UCS encodings and UTF-1).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] UTF-8 and UTF-16 are the most commonly used encodings.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] UCS-2 is an obsolete subset of UTF-16; UCS-4 and UTF-32 are functionally equivalent.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] UTF-8 uses one to four 8-bit units (*bytes*) per code point and, being compact for Latin scripts and ASCII-compatible, provides the de facto standard encoding for the interchange of Unicode text.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] It is used by FreeBSD and most recent Linux distributions as a direct replacement for legacy encodings in general text handling.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The UCS-2 and UTF-16 encodings specify the Unicode byte order mark (BOM) for use at the beginnings of text files, which may be used for byte-order detection (or byte endianness detection).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The same character converted to UTF-8 becomes the byte sequence `EF BB BF`.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] *The Unicode Standard* allows the BOM "can serve as a signature for UTF-8 encoded text where the character set is unmarked".
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Some software developers have adopted it for other encodings, including UTF-8, in an attempt to distinguish UTF-8 from local 8-bit code pages.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] However RFC 3629, the UTF-8 standard, recommends that byte order marks be forbidden in protocols using UTF-8, but discusses the cases where this may not be possible.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] In addition, the large restriction on possible patterns in UTF-8 (for instance there cannot be any lone bytes with the high bit set) means that it should be possible to distinguish UTF-8 from other character encodings without relying on the BOM.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] In UTF-32 and UCS-4, one 32-bit code unit serves as a fairly direct representation of any character's code point (although the endianness, which varies across different platforms, affects how the code unit manifests as a byte sequence).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] In the other encodings, each code point may be represented by a variable number of code units.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] UTF-32 is widely used as an internal representation of text in programs (as opposed to stored or transmitted text), since every Unix operating system that uses the GCC compilers to generate software uses it as the standard "wide character" encoding.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Recent versions of the Python programming language (beginning with 2.2) may also be configured to use UTF-32 as the representation for Unicode strings, effectively disseminating such encoding in high-level coded software.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Punycode, another encoding form, enables the encoding of Unicode strings into the limited character set supported by the ASCII-based Domain Name System (DNS).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The encoding is used as part of IDNA, which is a system enabling the use of Internationalized Domain Names in all scripts that are supported by Unicode.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] Earlier and now historical proposals include UTF-5 and UTF-6.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] GB18030 is another encoding form for Unicode, from the Standardization Administration of China.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] It is the official character set of the People's Republic of China (PRC).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] BOCU-1 and SCSU are Unicode compression schemes.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p01] The April Fools' Day RFC of 2005 specified two parody UTF encodings, UTF-9 and UTF-18.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Unicode, in the form of UTF-8, has been the most common encoding for the World Wide Web since 2008.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] It has near-universal adoption, and much of the non-UTF-8 content is found in other Unicode encodings, e.g.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] As of 2024, UTF-8 accounts for on average 98.3% of all web pages (and 983 of the top 1,000 highest-ranked web pages).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Although many pages only use ASCII characters to display content, UTF-8 was designed with 8-bit ASCII as a subset and almost no websites now declare their encoding to only be ASCII instead of UTF-8.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Over a third of the languages tracked have 100% UTF-8 use.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] All internet protocols maintained by Internet Engineering Task Force, e.g.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] File Transfer Protocol (FTP), have required support for UTF-8 since the publication of RFC 2277 in 1998, which specified that all IETF protocols "MUST be able to use the UTF-8 charset".
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Unicode has become the dominant scheme for the internal processing and storage of text.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Although a great deal of text is still stored in legacy encodings, Unicode is used almost exclusively for building new information processing systems.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Early adopters tended to use UCS-2 (the fixed-length two-byte obsolete precursor to UTF-16) and later moved to UTF-16 (the variable-length current standard), as this was the least disruptive way to add support for non-BMP characters.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] The best known such system is Windows NT (and its descendants, 2000, XP, Vista, 7, 8, 10, and 11), which uses UTF-16 as the sole internal character encoding.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] The Java and .NET bytecode environments, macOS, and KDE also use it for internal representation.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Partial support for Unicode can be installed on Windows 9x through the Microsoft Layer for Unicode.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] UTF-8 (originally developed for Plan 9) has become the main storage encoding on most Unix-like operating systems (though others are also used by some libraries) because it is a relatively easy replacement for traditional extended ASCII character sets.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] UTF-8 is also the most common Unicode encoding used in HTML documents on the World Wide Web.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Multilingual text-rendering engines which use Unicode include Uniscribe and DirectWrite for Microsoft Windows, ATSUI and Core Text for macOS, and Pango for GTK+ and the GNOME desktop.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Because keyboard layouts cannot have simple key combinations for all characters, several operating systems provide alternative input methods that allow access to the entire repertoire.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] ISO/IEC 14755, which standardises methods for entering Unicode characters from their code points, specifies several methods.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] There is the *Basic method*, where a *beginning sequence* is followed by the hexadecimal representation of the code point and the *ending sequence*.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] There is also a *screen-selection entry method* specified, where the characters are listed in a table on a screen, such as with a character map program.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Online tools for finding the code point for a known character include Unicode Lookup by Jonathan Hedley and Shapecatcher by Benjamin Milde.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] In Unicode Lookup, one enters a search key (e.g.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] "fractions"), and a list of corresponding characters with their code points is returned.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] In Shapecatcher, based on Shape context, one draws the character in a box and a list of characters approximating the drawing, with their code points, is returned.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] MIME defines two different mechanisms for encoding non-ASCII characters in email, depending on whether the characters are in email headers (such as the "Subject:"), or in the text body of the message; in both cases, the original character set is identified as well as a transfer encoding.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] For email transmission of Unicode, the UTF-8 character set and the Base64 or the Quoted-printable transfer encoding are recommended, depending on whether much of the message consists of ASCII characters.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] The details of the two different mechanisms are specified in the MIME standards and generally are hidden from users of email software.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] The IETF has defined a framework for internationalized email using UTF-8, and has updated several protocols in accordance with that framework.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] The adoption of Unicode in email has been very slow.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Some East Asian text is still encoded in encodings such as ISO-2022, and some devices, such as mobile phones, still cannot correctly handle Unicode data.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Many major free mail providers such as Yahoo!
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Mail, Gmail, and Outlook.com support it.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] All W3C recommendations have used Unicode as their *document character set* since HTML 4.0.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Web browsers have supported Unicode, especially UTF-8, for many years.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] There used to be display problems resulting primarily from font related issues; e.g. v6 and older of Microsoft Internet Explorer did not render many code points unless explicitly told to use a font that contains them.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] HTML characters manifest either directly as bytes according to the document's encoding, if the encoding supports them, or users may write them as numeric character references based on the character's Unicode code point.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] When specifying URIs, for example as URLs in HTTP requests, non-ASCII characters must be percent-encoded.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Unicode is not in principle concerned with fonts *per se*, seeing them as implementation choices.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Any given character may have many allographs, from the more common bold, italic and base letterforms to complex decorative styles.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] A font is "Unicode compliant" if the glyphs in the font can be accessed using code points defined in *The Unicode Standard*.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] The standard does not specify a minimum number of characters that must be included in the font; some fonts have quite a small repertoire.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Free and retail fonts based on Unicode are widely available, since TrueType and OpenType support Unicode (and Web Open Font Format (WOFF and WOFF2) is based on those).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] These font formats map Unicode code points to glyphs, but OpenType and TrueType font files are restricted to 65,535 glyphs.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Collection files provide a "gap mode" mechanism for overcoming this limit in a single font file.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] (Each font within the collection still has the 65,535 limit, however.) A TrueType Collection file would typically have a file extension of ".ttc".
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Thousands of fonts exist on the market, but fewer than a dozen fonts—sometimes described as "pan-Unicode" fonts—attempt to support the majority of Unicode's character repertoire.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Instead, Unicode-based fonts typically focus on supporting only basic ASCII and particular scripts or sets of characters or symbols.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Furthermore, designing a consistent set of rendering instructions for tens of thousands of glyphs constitutes a monumental task; such a venture passes the point of diminishing returns for most typefaces.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Unicode partially addresses the newline problem that occurs when trying to read a text file on different platforms.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Unicode defines a large number of characters that conforming applications should recognize as line terminators.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] In terms of the newline, Unicode introduced U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR and U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] This was an attempt to provide a Unicode solution to encoding paragraphs and lines semantically, potentially replacing all of the various platform solutions.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] In doing so, Unicode does provide a way around the historical platform-dependent solutions.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Nonetheless, few if any Unicode solutions have adopted these Unicode line and paragraph separators as the sole canonical line ending characters.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] However, a common approach to solving this issue is through newline normalization.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] This is achieved with the Cocoa text system in macOS and also with W3C XML and HTML recommendations.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] In this approach, every possible newline character is converted internally to a common newline (which one does not really matter since it is an internal operation just for rendering).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] In other words, the text system can correctly treat the character as a newline, regardless of the input's actual encoding.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] The Ideographic Research Group (IRG) is tasked with advising the Consortium and ISO regarding Han unification, or Unihan, especially the further addition of CJK unified and compatibility ideographs to the repertoire.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] The IRG is composed of experts from each region that has historically used Chinese characters.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] However, despite the deliberation within the committee, Han unification has consistently been one of the most contested aspects of *The Unicode Standard* since the genesis of the project.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Unicode's character model for CJK characters was based on the unification criteria used by JIS X 0208, as well as those developed by the Association for a Common Chinese Code in China.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Due to the standard's principle of encoding semantic instead of stylistic variants, Unicode has received criticism for not assigning code points to certain rare and archaic kanji variants, possibly complicating processing of ancient and uncommon Japanese names.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Since it places particular emphasis on Chinese, Japanese and Korean sharing many characters in common, Han unification is also sometimes perceived as treating the three as the same thing.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Less-frequently-used alternative encodings exist, often predating Unicode, with character models differing from this paradigm, aimed at preserving the various stylistic differences between regional and/or nonstandard character forms.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] One example is the TRON Code favored by some users for handling historical Japanese text, though not widely adopted among the Japanese public.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Another is the CCCII encoding adopted by library systems in Hong Kong, Taiwan and the United States.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] These have their own drawbacks in general use, leading to the Big5 encoding (introduced in 1984, four years after CCCII) having become more common than CCCII outside of library systems.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Although work at Apple based on Research Libraries Group's CJK Thesaurus, which was used to maintain the EACC variant of CCCII, was one of the direct predecessors of Unicode's Unihan set, Unicode adopted the JIS-style unification model.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] The earliest version of Unicode had a repertoire of fewer than 21,000 Han characters, largely limited to those in relatively common modern usage.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] As of version 17.0, the standard now encodes more than 101,000 Han characters, and work is continuing to add thousands more—largely historical and dialectal variant characters used throughout the Sinosphere.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Modern typefaces provide a means to address some of the practical issues in depicting unified Han characters with various regional graphical representations.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] The 'locl' OpenType table allows a renderer to select a different glyph for each code point based on the text locale.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] The Unicode variation sequences can also provide in-text annotations for a desired glyph selection; this requires registration of the specific variant in the Ideographic Variation Database.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] The same OpenType 'locl' technique is used.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] For use in the Turkish alphabet and Azeri alphabet, Unicode includes a separate dotless lowercase I (ı) and a dotted uppercase I (İ).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] However, the usual ASCII letters are used for the lowercase dotted i and the uppercase dotless I, matching how they are handled in the earlier ISO 8859-9.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] As such, case-insensitive comparisons for those languages have to use different rules than case-insensitive comparisons for other languages using the Latin script.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] This can have security implications if, for example, sanitization code or access control relies on case-insensitive comparison.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] By contrast, the Icelandic eth (ð), the barred D (đ) and the retroflex D (ɖ), which usually look the same in uppercase (Đ), are given the opposite treatment, and encoded separately in both letter-cases (in contrast to the earlier ISO 6937, which unifies the uppercase forms).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Although it allows for case-insensitive comparison without needing to know the language of the text, this approach also has issues, requiring security measures relating to homoglyph attacks.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Whether the lowercase letter I is expected to retain its tittle when a diacritic applies also depends on local conventions.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Unicode has a large number of homoglyphs, many of which look very similar or identical to ASCII letters.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Substitution of these can make an identifier or URL that looks correct, but directs to a different location than expected.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Additionally, homoglyphs can also be used for manipulating the output of natural language processing (NLP) systems.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Mitigation requires disallowing these characters, displaying them differently, or requiring that they resolve to the same identifier; all of this is complicated due to the huge and constantly changing set of characters.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] A security advisory was released in 2021 by two researchers, one from the University of Cambridge and the other from the University of Edinburgh, in which they assert that the BiDi marks can be used to make large sections of code do something different from what they appear to do.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] In response, code editors started highlighting marks to indicate forced text-direction changes.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] The UTF-8 and UTF-16 encodings do not accept all possible sequences of code units.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Implementations vary in what they do when reading an invalid sequence, which has led to security bugs.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Unicode was designed to provide code-point-by-code-point round-trip format conversion to and from any preexisting character encodings, so that text files in older character sets can be converted to Unicode and then back and get back the same file, without employing context-dependent interpretation.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] That has meant that inconsistent legacy architectures, such as combining diacritics and precomposed characters, both exist in Unicode, giving more than one method of representing some text.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] This is most pronounced in the three different encoding forms for Korean Hangul.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Since version 3.0, any precomposed characters that can be represented by a combined sequence of already existing characters can no longer be added to the standard to preserve interoperability between software using different versions of Unicode.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Injective mappings must be provided between characters in existing legacy character sets and characters in Unicode to facilitate conversion to Unicode and allow interoperability with legacy software.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Some Japanese computer programmers objected to Unicode because it requires them to separate the use of U+005C \ REVERSE SOLIDUS (backslash) and U+00A5 ¥ YEN SIGN, which was mapped to 0x5C in JIS X 0201, and a lot of legacy code exists with this usage.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] (This encoding also replaces tilde '~' 0x7E with macron '¯', now 0xAF.) The separation of these characters exists in ISO 8859-1, from long before Unicode.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Indic scripts such as Tamil and Devanagari are each allocated only 128 code points, matching the ISCII standard.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] The correct rendering of Unicode Indic text requires transforming the stored logical order characters into visual order and the forming of ligatures (also known as conjuncts) out of components.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Some local scholars argued in favor of assignments of Unicode code points to these ligatures, going against the practice for other writing systems, though Unicode contains some Arabic and other ligatures for backward compatibility purposes only.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Encoding of any new ligatures in Unicode will not happen, in part, because the set of ligatures is font-dependent, and Unicode is an encoding independent of font variations.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] The same kind of issue arose for the Tibetan script in 2003 when the Standardization Administration of China proposed encoding 956 precomposed Tibetan syllables, but these were rejected for encoding by the relevant ISO committee (ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 2).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Thai alphabet support has been criticized for its ordering of Thai characters.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] The vowels เ, แ, โ, ใ, ไ that are written to the left of the preceding consonant are in visual order instead of phonetic order, unlike the Unicode representations of other Indic scripts.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] This complication is due to Unicode inheriting the Thai Industrial Standard 620, which worked in the same way, and was the way in which Thai had always been written on keyboards.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] This ordering problem complicates the Unicode collation process slightly, requiring table lookups to reorder Thai characters for collation.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Even if Unicode had adopted encoding according to spoken order, it would still be problematic to collate words in dictionary order.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] E.g., the word แสดง [sa dɛːŋ] "perform" starts with a consonant cluster "สด" (with an inherent vowel for the consonant "ส"), the vowel แ-, in spoken order would come after the ด, but in a dictionary, the word is collated as it is written, with the vowel following the ส.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Characters with diacritical marks can generally be represented either as a single precomposed character or as a decomposed sequence of a base letter plus one or more non-spacing marks.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] Similarly, underdots, as needed in the romanization of Indic languages, will often be placed incorrectly.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] While Unicode defines the script designator (name) to be "Phags_Pa", in that script's character names, a hyphen is added: U+A840 ꡀ PHAGS-PA LETTER KA.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/unicode-p02] This, however, is not an anomaly, but the rule: hyphens are replaced by underscores in script designators.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] It’s been available across browsers since March 2017.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] The **`writing-mode`** CSS property sets whether lines of text are laid out horizontally or vertically, as well as the direction in which blocks progress.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] When set for an entire document, it should be set on the root element (`html` element for HTML documents).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] This property specifies the *block flow direction*, which is the direction in which block-level containers are stacked, and the direction in which inline-level content flows within a block container.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] Thus, it also determines the ordering of block-level content.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] The `writing-mode` property is specified as one of the values listed below.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] The flow direction in horizontal scripts is also affected by the directionality of that script, either left-to-right (`ltr`, like English and most other languages) or right-to-left (`rtl`, like Hebrew or Arabic).
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] For `ltr` scripts, content flows horizontally from left to right.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] For `rtl` scripts, content flows horizontally from right to left.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] The next horizontal line is positioned below the previous line.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] For `ltr` scripts, content flows vertically from top to bottom, and the next vertical line is positioned to the left of the previous line.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] For `rtl` scripts, content flows vertically from bottom to top, and the next vertical line is positioned to the left of the previous line.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] For `ltr` scripts, content flows vertically from top to bottom, and the next vertical line is positioned to the right of the previous line.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] For `rtl` scripts, content flows vertically from bottom to top, and the next vertical line is positioned to the right of the previous line.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] For `ltr` scripts, content flows vertically from top to bottom.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] For `rtl` scripts, content flows vertically from bottom to top.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] All the glyphs, even those in vertical scripts, are set sideways toward the right.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] For `ltr` scripts, content flows vertically from bottom to top.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] For `rtl` scripts, content flows vertically from top to bottom.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] All the glyphs, even those in vertical scripts, are set sideways toward the left.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] This example demonstrates all of the writing modes, showing each with text in various languages.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] The HTML is a `<table>` with each writing mode in a row with a column showing text in various scripts using that writing mode.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] If your browser doesn't support `sideways-lr`, a workaround is to use `transform` to achieve a similar effect depending on the script direction.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] The effect of `vertical-rl` is the same as with `sideways-lr`, so no transformation is required for left-to-right scripts.
[src:unicode-bidi-web/writing-mode] In some cases, rotating the text 180 degrees is sufficient to achieve the effect of `sideways-lr`, but font glyphs may not be designed to be rotated, so this may produce unexpected positioning or rendering.
